{"user_query": "How to avoid foot infections ?", "answer": "To avoid foot infections, individuals with diabetes should follow these key steps for proper foot care:\n\n1. Check your feet daily for any red spots, cuts, swelling, blisters, or other abnormalities. Use a mirror or seek assistance to inspect the bottom of your feet thoroughly.\n2. Wash your feet daily with mild soap and water, ensuring to dry them carefully, especially between the toes.\n3. Moisturize your feet daily to keep the skin soft and smooth, but avoid applying moisturizer between the toes.\n4. Regularly inspect and file away hard skin patches on the soles of your feet to prevent ulcers from forming.\n5. Keep your toenails trimmed by cutting them straight across and filing the edges, avoiding cutting into the sides to prevent ingrown nails.\n6. Always wear comfortable, well-fitting shoes and socks to protect your feet and prevent injuries. Avoid walking barefoot.\n7. Maintain good blood circulation to the feet by elevating them when sitting and performing regular toe and ankle exercises.\n8. Avoid smoking, as it can harm blood circulation and increase the risk of complications.\n\nBy diligently following these foot care practices, individuals with diabetes can reduce the risk of foot infections and related complications.", "source_docs": [{"source_doc": "Blister, wound, corn, and callus\n\nRedness, swelling, bruise, or increased warmth\n\nToenail anomaly or change in foot shape\n\nMaintain good foot care and hygiene\n\nClean feet daily with mild soap and water\n\nDry thoroughly between each toe\n\nUse a pumice stone or foot file to gently remove hard skin\n\nAvoid cutting nails too short; cut them straight across and file corners\n\nAvoid cutting nails too short; cut them straight across and file corners\n\nMoisturise hard skin areas regularly\n\nAvoid using harsh soap\n\nApply moisturiser daily but not between each toe\n\nAvoid scratching skin as it may lead to wound or bleeding\n\n51\n\nHome san